3-2-1 rule. 3 copies of your data, at least on 2 separate media, and at least 1 off-site. There are many ways to go about it, you can simply use multiple hard drives to have multiple copies of your data, or you can go beyond that and look into things like LTO tapes or M-Disc Blu-Rays, and as far as off-site backups go you can set up a NAS at your parent's house and access it via a WireGuard tunnel, collocate your own backup server, pay for a VPS service or just a regular backup service like Backblaze and get things encrypted before you upload it there, though you should encrypt local drives as well. As long as you have at least two copies of your data you're already better off than 99% of the population that keeps everything on their laptop or smartphone, then get shocked and appalled when they've permanently lost their baby photos because they dropped their phone in a toilet and no, no tech wizardry can bring those photos back at this point since their phone memory was soldered on and encrypted.
